00:46:53.730 --> 00:46:55.833
There's a wealth of information there.

00:46:59.080 --> 00:47:00.920
I wanna talk a little bit about

00:47:00.920 --> 00:47:03.040
one of our newer resources

00:47:03.040 --> 00:47:06.360
which is on communication access.

00:47:06.360 --> 00:47:10.730
The most important accommodation
for any appointment

00:47:10.730 --> 00:47:12.113
is communication.

00:47:13.180 --> 00:47:16.133
Communication is the
foundation of patient care.

00:47:17.040 --> 00:47:19.210
Everybody communicates.

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:20.173
Find a way!

00:47:21.210 --> 00:47:23.930
Supporters are important
and, with permission,

00:47:23.930 --> 00:47:26.650
can certainly provide a lot of information

00:47:26.650 --> 00:47:28.860
that's helpful to supplement,

00:47:28.860 --> 00:47:31.490
but only a patient can tell you

00:47:31.490 --> 00:47:33.350
about their thoughts, feelings

00:47:33.350 --> 00:47:36.490
and internal experiences and motivations.

00:47:36.490 --> 00:47:38.530
And I'll tell you a
little story about this.

00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:43.110
I had an autistic patient
who came in with her sister

00:47:43.110 --> 00:47:44.760
who didn't actually
know her all that well,

00:47:44.760 --> 00:47:46.630
because her mother had
been providing her care

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:49.390
and her mother passed away, unfortunately,

00:47:49.390 --> 00:47:53.730
before she assisted with
making an accommodation letter

00:47:53.730 --> 00:47:54.710
'cause had she done that,

00:47:54.710 --> 00:47:56.460
we would have been in better shape.

00:47:57.450 --> 00:48:01.300
But, the sister was very insistent

00:48:01.300 --> 00:48:03.730
that she could not
provide me with a history.

00:48:03.730 --> 00:48:05.180
And she thought something was wrong,

00:48:05.180 --> 00:48:06.610
but she didn't know what.

00:48:06.610 --> 00:48:10.610
And, she was non-speaking

00:48:10.610 --> 00:48:12.150
and I didn't know how
to communicate with her

00:48:12.150 --> 00:48:14.340
and had no information from her supporter.

00:48:14.340 --> 00:48:17.207
So, I said, "Well, we
don't know what's going on.

00:48:17.207 --> 00:48:18.580
"Let's just try."

00:48:18.580 --> 00:48:20.870
So I just, I didn't know what to do,

00:48:20.870 --> 00:48:22.220
but I just started trying things.

00:48:22.220 --> 00:48:23.840
So I sat her in front of my computer

00:48:23.840 --> 00:48:25.610
to see if she'd type, and she did type,

00:48:25.610 --> 00:48:27.740
but nothing that I could interpret.

00:48:27.740 --> 00:48:31.280
And then I tried giving her choices.

00:48:31.280 --> 00:48:32.160
That didn't work.

00:48:32.160 --> 00:48:37.160
I pulled out, I have a
bunch of anatomy pictures,

00:48:38.190 --> 00:48:39.520
and I pulled them out

00:48:39.520 --> 00:48:41.660
and flipped through the anatomy pictures

00:48:41.660 --> 00:48:44.930
to see if she would light
up or point to anything.

00:48:44.930 --> 00:48:48.270
And, I said, "Show me how you say yes,"

00:48:48.270 --> 00:48:49.600
and observed carefully

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:53.650
to see if she would make
a sound or make a motion

00:48:53.650 --> 00:48:55.500
or make an expression that might help me

00:48:55.500 --> 00:48:57.970
to understand how she says yes and no.

00:48:57.970 --> 00:48:59.950
And that didn't work.

00:48:59.950 --> 00:49:02.910
So, I just said, "Touch hurt."

00:49:02.910 --> 00:49:05.060
And she took my hand

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:07.533
and she put it on her
right upper-quadrant,

00:49:09.270 --> 00:49:11.770
and, based solely on that communication,

00:49:11.770 --> 00:49:15.283
I ordered a sonogram
and she had gallstones.

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:19.123
It's a really hard diagnosis
to make without a history.

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:22.550
And without her help,

00:49:22.550 --> 00:49:23.525
her sister didn't know,

00:49:23.525 --> 00:49:26.923
I would have never made that
diagnosis without her help.

00:49:30.730 --> 00:49:33.862
I wouldn't say that I always have success,

00:49:33.862 --> 00:49:38.862
but my success rate is, and
all of our success rate,

00:49:39.040 --> 00:49:39.873
is a lot higher when we try. (laughs)

00:49:39.873 --> 00:49:42.562
(audience laughs)

00:49:46.410 --> 00:49:47.810
And I'm often surprised.

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:51.194
I'm often skeptical that
my efforts will go anywhere

00:49:51.194 --> 00:49:54.543
and, more often than not, they do.

00:49:54.543 --> 00:49:58.350
Just the effort sends a
message to the patient

00:49:58.350 --> 00:50:00.320
that makes them try harder too.

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:02.200
So, if you're not trying,

00:50:02.200 --> 00:50:03.810
They're so used to being ignored.

00:50:03.810 --> 00:50:06.580
They're so used to not having
people engage like that

00:50:06.580 --> 00:50:08.880
that there's often a lot
of learned helplessness

00:50:08.880 --> 00:50:10.600
and they can actually
communicate a lot better

00:50:10.600 --> 00:50:12.200
than they typically do

00:50:12.200 --> 00:50:14.170
because they don't think
anyone's listening.

00:50:14.170 --> 00:50:15.570
So why would you try

00:50:15.570 --> 00:50:18.510
if you don't think
anyone's paying attention?

00:50:18.510 --> 00:50:20.660
And also, without some of that support,

00:50:20.660 --> 00:50:21.817
like, "Touch hurt,"

00:50:22.680 --> 00:50:25.630
she might not have thought that
I would have interpret her,

00:50:26.580 --> 00:50:28.990
Maybe she would have thought that,

00:50:28.990 --> 00:50:29.860
she would have been afraid that

00:50:29.860 --> 00:50:33.030
I would interpret her taking
my hand and putting it on her

00:50:33.030 --> 00:50:35.491
as an act of aggression
or something like that

00:50:35.491 --> 00:50:37.391
and would have been too afraid to try.

00:50:42.381 --> 00:50:44.710
So, we have a tool.

00:50:44.710 --> 00:50:48.040
So, many patients come

00:50:48.040 --> 00:50:52.420
without a fluent form of
expressive communication

00:50:52.420 --> 00:50:53.750
available to them.

00:50:53.750 --> 00:50:56.730
And, this is one of our newest resources,

00:50:56.730 --> 00:50:58.930
which is a Communication Toolkit,

00:50:58.930 --> 00:51:01.428
that was also developed
in collaboration with

00:51:01.428 --> 00:51:05.070
self-advocates from the
Autistic Self Advocacy Network

00:51:05.070 --> 00:51:06.682
and it includes practical advice

00:51:06.682 --> 00:51:10.610
on how to recognize good
communication supports.

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:14.800
The components of a good
assessment that take into account

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:18.130
sensory, motor, and cognitive impairments.

00:51:18.130 --> 00:51:20.980
It discusses how to choose
an assessment professional

00:51:20.980 --> 00:51:25.480
and how to get supports
and assessments funded.

00:51:25.480 --> 00:51:27.133
So, I hope you'll use that.

00:51:39.560 --> 00:51:41.940
- Thank you so much for listening to us

00:51:41.940 --> 00:51:43.533
at the very end of the day.

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:47.910
From this work we've learned
that our CBPR process

00:51:47.910 --> 00:51:49.950
has resulted in a highly-accessible

00:51:49.950 --> 00:51:52.480
and usable healthcare toolkit.

00:51:52.480 --> 00:51:55.690
It has the potential to
decrease barriers to healthcare,

00:51:55.690 --> 00:51:57.600
improve healthcare self-efficacy

00:51:57.600 --> 00:51:59.713
in patient-provider communication.

00:52:00.940 --> 00:52:03.770
We're currently testing it
in some healthcare systems

00:52:03.770 --> 00:52:07.180
because we don't, even
though things got better,

00:52:07.180 --> 00:52:10.090
that's not really good efficacy data yet.

00:52:10.090 --> 00:52:13.500
So we're working toward
getting real efficacy data.

00:52:13.500 --> 00:52:15.490
And changes might have been driven by

00:52:15.490 --> 00:52:19.230
changes in self-awareness
and self-advocacy, as well as

00:52:19.230 --> 00:52:24.230
changes by patient and provider
behaviors or attitudes.

00:52:26.550 --> 00:52:27.850
So the implications.

00:52:27.850 --> 00:52:30.670
Please use our toolkits.

00:52:30.670 --> 00:52:33.750
They are available for free here.

00:52:33.750 --> 00:52:38.750
The tools may be helpful to
patients with other disabilities

00:52:38.850 --> 00:52:41.760
or even just patients
with low health literacy.

00:52:41.760 --> 00:52:45.370
There's a lot of teaching things about

00:52:45.370 --> 00:52:48.113
just how the healthcare
system works on the site.

00:52:49.180 --> 00:52:51.480
Healthcare systems should find ways

00:52:51.480 --> 00:52:54.980
to incorporate these tools
into their clinical practice.

00:52:54.980 --> 00:52:59.290
And, other groups attempting
to develop stuff of any sort

00:52:59.290 --> 00:53:00.710
from marginalized populations

00:53:00.710 --> 00:53:04.923
should consider using a CBPR approach.

